&lt;p&gt;Please join the Harriman Institute for a Russian History Workshop with &lt;strong&gt;Zukhra Kasimova&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This paper&amp;nbsp;reconstructs&amp;nbsp;arguably the most renowned wartime Soviet adoption story&amp;nbsp;of the Uzbek adoptive parents (Sha)Akhmed Shamakhmudov and Bakhri Akramova. By placing the family story in the broader sociopolitical context, this paper underscores the role of regional political actors in reconfiguring the Soviet postwar &amp;ldquo;Friendship of the Peoples&amp;rdquo; paradigm and decenters the symbolic role of Slavic/Russian &amp;ldquo;elder brother&amp;rdquo; in the multiethnic Soviet &amp;ldquo;family of nations.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interested participants should contact &lt;strong&gt;Taylor Zajicek&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;a href="mailto:tcz2107@columbia.edu"&gt;tcz2107@columbia.edu&lt;/a&gt;) to receive a copy of the paper in advance of the workshop.&lt;/p&gt;

