&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Music Monday&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;is a free and open-to-the public monthly concert series hosted by The Forum. Performances&amp;nbsp;take place in The Forum&amp;#39;s ground-floor Atrium on Monday evenings, once a month. &lt;a href="https://www.eventbrite.com/e/holiday-caroling-at-the-forum-registration-998662866517" target="_blank"&gt;RSVP is encouraged&lt;/a&gt;. Please visit The Forum&amp;#39;s website for the full&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://theforum.columbia.edu/events" target="_blank"&gt;calendar of events&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For December&amp;#39;s event, The Forum will host&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.everyvoicechoirs.org/" target="_blank"&gt;Every Voice Choirs&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;for a special &amp;quot;Community Caroling&amp;quot; holiday performance.&amp;nbsp;Performers will include chorus members from the Every Voice Kids Choir, Youth Choir, Concert Choir, and Hunter Singers. Get ready to sing along to your favorite holiday songs!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Based at Columbia University Teachers College,&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Every Voice Choirs&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is celebrating its tenth year of helping children discover their voices and share them with pride. Everyone is welcome in EVC&amp;#39;s core choirs -&lt;a href="https://www.everyvoicechoirs.org/every-voice-kids.html" target="_blank"&gt;&amp;nbsp;Kids Choir&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&lt;a href="https://www.everyvoicechoirs.org/evc-youth-choir.html" target="_blank"&gt;&amp;nbsp;Youth Choir&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;- without audition.&lt;a href="https://www.everyvoicechoirs.org/voiceability.html" target="_blank"&gt;&amp;nbsp;EVC VoiceAbility&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;is for children ages 9-13 with special needs.&amp;nbsp;EVC&amp;#39;s&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.everyvoicechoirs.org/evc-concert-choir.html" target="_blank"&gt;Concert Choir&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;performs challenging works in collaboration with premiere choirs and orchestras, including two performances at Carnegie Hall this season. EVC&amp;rsquo;s choirs have performed at Merkin Hall, Carnegie Hall, Madison Square Garden, and CitiField, as well as in film and television productions. EVC welcomes new singers - join us! Scholarships for residents of West Harlem. Learn more and sign up at&lt;a href="http://www.everyvoicechoirs.org/" target="_blank"&gt;&amp;nbsp;www.everyvoicechoirs.org&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On a snowy Winter&amp;rsquo;s day, Clement Clarke Moore (1779-1863),&amp;nbsp;a Columbia graduate,&amp;nbsp;composed&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;A Visit from St. Nicholas&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;which he read to his children on Christmas Eve, 1822. For over two hundred years children and adults alike have been enchanted by this classic poem. The visions of sugar plums, stockings hung by the chimney, a sleigh and eight tiny reindeer and of course, St. Nick -&amp;nbsp; with his twinkling eyes and cheeks like roses with a nose like a cherry, he was chubby and plump and looked like an elf -&amp;nbsp; have captured the imagination of people all over the world.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://dc.alumni.columbia.edu/pamelamccoll" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Join us&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;for a lively and informative presentation as Pamela McColl, historian and the author of&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.amazon.com/Twas-Night-History-Classic-Christmas/dp/1927979307"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;rsquo;Twas the Night: The Art and History of the Classic Christmas Poem&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;traces the evolution of the holiday, from which Moore&amp;rsquo;s literary work derives, from antiquity and the celebration of Saturnalia. She then discusses the two centuries of winter cultural traditions, as well as elements from religious and secular influences, in the creation of the poem.&amp;nbsp;McColl uses dozens of vintage illustrations from the thousands of editions published over the years as well as archival material from the Columbia University Archives&lt;em&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;She explores the influence of Washington Irving and the historic figure of St. Nicholas on Moore&amp;rsquo;s conception of the central figure of his holiday poem and considers how many of today&amp;rsquo;s characteristics of Santa Claus originated with Clement Moore.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Time will be allocated for Q&amp;amp;A.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;This event is co-sponsored&amp;nbsp;by ColumbiaDC. Please RSVP via ColumbiaDC&amp;#39;s event page here:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://dc.alumni.columbia.edu/pamelamccoll" target="_blank"&gt;https://dc.alumni.columbia.edu/pamelamccoll&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

